<h2>Sonic GT Characters</h2>

Sonic GT has <strong>4 main characters</strong> available from the start (Mighty unlocks during the first zone) and <strong>3 hidden unlockables</strong>. Each one shares the core moveset but has a unique ability that genuinely changes how you approach levels.

<div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:12px;margin:20px 0 32px">
<div class="details-box" style="margin:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column">
<h3 style="font-size:1.2em;margin:0 0 8px">Sonic</h3>
<p style="margin:0;font-size:0.95em;line-height:1.5;flex:1">The balanced starter with the highest slope influence in the game — perfect for learning the Bumper Engine. His <strong>Drop Dash</strong> lets him roll immediately on landing, and his Bounce is a key tool for gaining momentum and height. Good all-around stats make him ideal for first playthroughs.</p>
</div>
<div class="details-box" style="margin:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column">
<h3 style="font-size:1.2em;margin:0 0 8px">Mighty</h3>
<p style="margin:0;font-size:0.95em;line-height:1.5;flex:1">Unlocked during Ocean Paradise. <strong>Better roll speed, higher jumps, stronger acceleration</strong> but lower top speed. Invincible while rolling or jumping. His air roll works as a combined Stomp + Drop Dash ("Bounce Dash") — he slams down and launches forward at high speed. A direct evolution of his Mania playstyle into 3D.</p>
</div>
<div class="details-box" style="margin:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column">
<h3 style="font-size:1.2em;margin:0 0 8px">Ray</h3>
<p style="margin:0;font-size:0.95em;line-height:1.5;flex:1">Reward for completing the game. Incredible acceleration and jump height but poor overall stats. His <strong>Mania-style glide</strong> lets him cover massive distances in a single leap when launched with enough momentum — effectively skipping entire sections of a zone. Loses altitude when speed drops, so maintaining momentum is critical.</p>
</div>
<div class="details-box" style="margin:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column">
<h3 style="font-size:1.2em;margin:0 0 8px">Shadow</h3>
<p style="margin:0;font-size:0.95em;line-height:1.5;flex:1">Stats similar to Sonic with a notably <strong>faster Homing Attack</strong> that makes combat feel snappy. His <strong>Chaos Kick</strong> slows time, locks onto an enemy, and launches him skyward — flashy but cuts all momentum. Also has <strong>Chaos Control</strong> for temporary invincibility and devastating hits.</p>
</div>
</div>

<strong>Three hidden characters</strong> add even more replay value: <strong>Super Sonic</strong> (collect all Chaos Emeralds), <strong>Classic Sonic</strong> (find 4 hidden items in Hill Top — faster acceleration, higher jumps, shorter Homing Attack range), and <strong>Metal Sonic</strong> (find 4 items in Hidden Base — features a Chaos Boost that propels him forward like a missile, destroying enemies and attracting rings while draining your ring count).

<h2>Chaos Emerald System</h2>

Sonic GT includes a <strong>Chaos Emerald hunting system</strong> inspired by Sonic Adventure 2. A radar in the corner of the screen changes color based on your proximity to a hidden emerald — cold when far, hot when close. The clever part: <strong>emeralds collected with one character stay collected for all characters</strong>, which encourages replaying zones with different characters to access areas that specific abilities make easier to reach.

Collecting all 7 Chaos Emeralds unlocks <strong>Super Sonic</strong> as a playable character — an overpowered version of Sonic for those who want to blast through every zone at full speed.

<h2>What Could Be Better</h2>

Sonic GT is not without its rough edges. The <strong>boss fights are the weakest element</strong> — the Hill Top boss (a high-speed mole chase) is the only one that truly works with the game's momentum philosophy. The Sunset Boulevard boss traps you in a static arena that kills the flow, and the final boss is frustratingly inconsistent with attacks that sometimes hit without clear logic.

<strong>Combat</strong> is barebones: enemies exist mostly as Homing Attack targets, and ranged enemies can be annoying since they shoot during your attack animation. The <strong>camera</strong> has two modes — Auto (moves on its own and often poorly) and Free (works well except in some Hidden Base areas). And if you play with a controller, you will need to <strong>disconnect it in menus</strong> to avoid a bug that automatically backs out of submenus.

These issues are worth mentioning, but they do not overshadow the core experience. The momentum system and level design carry the game hard enough that the community consistently rates it among the best 3D Sonic fan games ever made.

<h2>Sonic GT FAQ</h2>

<div class="details-grid">
<details>
<summary>Is Sonic GT free to download?</summary>
<p>Yes, completely free. No account, no registration, no payments. Just download the ZIP and play.</p>
</details>
<details>
<summary>How many characters are in Sonic GT?</summary>
<p>7 total. Sonic, Mighty, Ray, and Shadow are the main four. Super Sonic, Classic Sonic, and Metal Sonic are unlockable through gameplay challenges.</p>
</details>
<details>
<summary>How do I unlock Metal Sonic?</summary>
<p>Find and collect 4 hidden items scattered throughout the Hidden Base zone. Metal Sonic has a unique Chaos Boost ability that propels him forward at high speed.</p>
</details>
<details>
<summary>How long is Sonic GT?</summary>
<p>A first playthrough takes roughly 2-3 hours across the 4 zones. Replaying with different characters, hunting Chaos Emeralds, and unlocking all hidden characters adds significant replay time.</p>
</details>
<details>
<summary>My controller doesn't work in menus</summary>
<p>This is a known bug. Disconnect your controller while navigating menus, then reconnect it once your level has loaded. Gameplay controls work fine.</p>
</details>
<details>
<summary>Which camera mode should I use?</summary>
<p>Use Free camera. The Auto camera moves on its own and often fights your input. Free camera gives you full control and works well in most areas.</p>
</details>
<details>
<summary>Is Sonic GT still being updated?</summary>
<p>The game was released as a complete experience at SAGE 2020 with 4 full zones, boss fights, and a final boss. It is a finished product, not a demo.</p>
</details>
<details>
<summary>Does Sonic GT run on Mac or Linux?</summary>
<p>No, it is Windows-only. There are no official Mac or Linux builds available.</p>
</details>
</div>
